{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08acc1ef-291f-4ae8-bfd2-5b399f026250","content":"In modern MSTest (3.8+), here's the recommended pattern using constructor injection for `TestContext` along with `[TestInitialize]` for async setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client;\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous init (called before each test)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        _client = await CreateAuthenticatedClientAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        _client?.Dispose();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        // use _client ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** — MSTest 3.x injects `TestContext` automatically via the constructor. No need for the legacy `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports `async Task` for async setup (runs before each test).\n- **`[ClassInitialize]`** — use a `static async Task` method if you need one-time async setup shared across all tests in the class.\n- Avoid putting async work in the constructor; use `[TestInitialize]` instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ba1c0d07-7ad3-4e74-8d38-ad1b39658624","outputTokens":367,"requestId":"BD0B:2A497:1DD9767:21C45E6:6A07CBB4"},"id":"2a555c40-a19f-4272-abb1-226e7fd4bb59","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:43:25.170Z","parentId":"0208bc28-f0ef-42bf-8bcc-5aa8585039d0"}
